Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is feature engineering?
AI Response

Feature engineering creates or transforms input variables using domain knowledge to improve model
performance. It includes scaling, encoding, and creating interaction terms.

Example 1.2

User

What is a transformer model?
AI Response

A transformer is a deep learning architecture using self-attention mechanisms that process all tokens in
parallel, enabling efficient NLP. GPT and BERT are transformer-based models.

Example 1.3

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.4

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.

Example 1.5

User

What is deep learning?
AI Response

Deep learning is a subset of machine learning that uses multi-layered neural networks to learn
representations of data. It excels at tasks like image recognition, NLP, and speech synthesis.

Example 1.6

User

What is word embedding?
AI Response

Word embeddings map words to dense vectors where similar words are nearby. Word2Vec, GloVe, and
FastText are popular methods, used as NLP model input features.

Example 1.7

User

What is a loss function?
AI Response



A loss function quantifies the difference between a model's predictions and the actual targets. Examples
include Mean Squared Error for regression and Cross-Entropy Loss for classification.

Example 1.8

User

What is a GAN?
AI Response

A Generative Adversarial Network pits a generator (creates fake data) against a discriminator (identifies
fakes), training each other until the generator produces realistic data.

Example 1.9

User

What is batch normalization?
AI Response

Batch normalization normalizes layer inputs to have zero mean and unit variance, stabilizing training,
reducing initialization sensitivity, and acting as a mild regularizer.

Example 1.10

User

What is overfitting?
AI Response

Overfitting occurs when a model learns training data too well—including noise—causing poor generalization
to new data. Symptoms include high train accuracy but low validation accuracy.



